1️⃣ Explain Account Takeover and how you secure against it.
“In an e-commerce system, account takeover is not just unauthorized login. It is a financial fraud vector. Once an attacker controls an account, they can manipulate wallet balance, stored cards, refunds, addresses, loyalty points, and coupon flows. 
So I treat ATO as both an authentication and fraud problem.”

2️⃣ How ATO Happens
🔹 Credential Stuffing
	• Attackers use breached credential dumps.
	• Automated bots attempt login across accounts.
	• They rotate IPs via botnets.
	• They randomize headers to bypass simple rate limits.
	• They distribute attempts across time to avoid lockouts.
Important line:
“Credential stuffing is low-and-slow now. It's no longer brute force in a single burst.”

🔹 OTP Brute Force / MFA Abuse
Common mistakes:
	• 4-digit OTP with no rate limit.
	• OTP valid for too long.
	• No lockout after repeated failures.
Even more advanced:
	• MFA fatigue attack (spamming push notifications until user clicks approve).
	• SIM swap attack targeting SMS-based OTP.

🔹 Session Hijacking
	• If XSS exists → token theft.
	• If cookies lack HttpOnly → accessible via JS.
	• If SameSite not configured → CSRF-like session abuse.
	• If session ID predictable → session fixation.

🔹 Password Reset Abuse
	“Is password reset endpoint sensitive?”
Answer:
“Yes. It is one of the most attacked endpoints.
If reset tokens are predictable, not expiring, or reusable, ATO becomes trivial.”
	• Token entropy must be high.
	• Single-use tokens.
	• Short expiry.
	• Invalidate after use.

3️⃣ Why Basic Rate Limiting Is Not Enough
“Traditional per-IP rate limiting fails because attackers distribute traffic across botnets. Modern attacks use residential proxies and legitimate user agents.”
“Static CAPTCHA also fails because solving services exist.”

4️⃣ Detection Engineering
“I would design ATO detection using layered signals.”
Layer 1: Authentication Signals
	• Failed login spike
	• Password spraying patterns (one password across many users)
	• Login attempt entropy anomalies
Layer 2: Session Risk Signals
	• New device fingerprint
	• New ASN / ISP
	• Geo velocity anomaly
	• Headless browser detection
Layer 3: Post-login Behavior
	• Immediate change of email/password
	• Rapid checkout
	• Adding new payment method
	• Multiple refund requests
“I would assign a dynamic risk score per session rather than binary allow/block.”

5️⃣ Prevention Architecture (How You Design It)
Authentication Hardening
	• Strong password hashing (bcrypt/argon2)
	• Constant-time comparison
	• Account lockout with exponential backoff
	• Progressive delay after failures

Token Strategy
	• Short-lived access tokens (10–15 min)
	• Rotating refresh tokens
	• Refresh token reuse detection
	• Token binding to device (if possible)
“If a refresh token is used twice, assume compromise and revoke session family.”

Adaptive MFA
	• Only trigger when risk score high.
	• Do not prompt on every login (bad UX).
	• Use device recognition.

